# Define Account Object Naming Conventions

## Overview

This section defines the naming conventions for account-level objects in our Snowflake platform. Consistent naming standards enable easier identification of resources, clearer governance, streamlined automation, and effective FinOps cost allocation.

## Decision Summary

| Decision | Selection |
|----------|-----------|
| **Component Order** | `{{ object_component_order }}` |
| **Domain Required** | {{ require_domain_in_objects }} |
| **Environment Required** | {{ require_env_in_objects }} |
| **Data Product Required** | {{ require_dataproduct_in_objects }} |

## Component Ordering

**Selected Order:** `{{ object_component_order }}`

{%- if object_component_order == "<domain>_<env>_<dataproduct>" %}
Objects will be named with **Domain first, then Environment, then Data Product**.
- Clusters objects by business domain first
- Groups environments within each domain
- Data products are the final differentiator

**Example:** `FIN_PROD_ANALYTICS`
{%- elif object_component_order == "<domain>_<dataproduct>_<env>" %}
Objects will be named with **Domain first, then Data Product, then Environment**.
- Clusters objects by business domain first
- Groups data products within each domain
- Environment is the final differentiator

**Example:** `FIN_ANALYTICS_PROD`
{%- elif object_component_order == "<env>_<domain>_<dataproduct>" %}
Objects will be named with **Environment first, then Domain, then Data Product**.
- Clusters objects by environment first (all prod together, all dev together)
- Groups domains within each environment
- Data products are the final differentiator

**Example:** `PROD_FIN_ANALYTICS`
{%- endif %}

